Erasmus is equally fastidious in the varying style of these four hymns. As we would expect, he eschews the accentual, rhyming patterns of most medieval hymns. The hymn to St. Gregory is wn'tten in third-asclepiadean strophes, rare during the later Middle Ages until they were revived by the humanists in the fifteenth century. The hymn to Gregory is brief, plain, dignified, instructive‚ entirely suited for actual use as a matins hymn.
